WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.499 --> 00:00:03.190
BOB MEESE: Thank you for coming
to the Games panel today.

00:00:03.190 --> 00:00:06.400
The overall topic is
around bringing your games

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:07.600
internationally.

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:10.310
And so we have five
fine gentlemen here

00:00:10.310 --> 00:00:12.354
who will tell you some stories.

00:00:12.354 --> 00:00:14.520
I want to make this as
interactive as possible, too,

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:18.155
so if there are anything that
you guys want to hear about,

00:00:18.155 --> 00:00:20.280
we have a mic that we'll
bring around as well, too.

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:23.090
So we can take
questions at any point.

00:00:23.090 --> 00:00:25.940
This time is for
all of you today.

00:00:25.940 --> 00:00:29.789
And we had a nice, lively email
exchange leading up to this.

00:00:29.789 --> 00:00:31.830
So we definitely have some
opinions on the panel.

00:00:31.830 --> 00:00:33.800
But a great group of guys.

00:00:33.800 --> 00:00:38.140
So if you guys have any other
questions or topics to suggest,

00:00:38.140 --> 00:00:39.420
please do that.

00:00:39.420 --> 00:00:42.830
But just first want to start off
by having these guys just spend

00:00:42.830 --> 00:00:45.650
30 seconds just
introducing themselves,

00:00:45.650 --> 00:00:48.120
their company, and then
any specific experience

00:00:48.120 --> 00:00:50.860
around bringing your games
to international markets,

00:00:50.860 --> 00:00:53.120
just to kind of introduce
everybody at the start here.

00:00:55.455 --> 00:00:56.580
SAAD CHOUDRI: Hi, everyone.

00:00:56.580 --> 00:00:59.680
I'm Saad Choudri from Miniclip.

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:04.610
We're probably best known in the
app stores for "8 Ball Pool."

00:01:04.610 --> 00:01:07.970
So if you haven't played
that, check it out.

00:01:07.970 --> 00:01:10.919
We also publish James
Vaughan's "Plague Inc"--

00:01:10.919 --> 00:01:12.960
I'll give him a shout,
because he's right there--

00:01:12.960 --> 00:01:15.390
on the Android platform.

00:01:15.390 --> 00:01:19.750
And because we started
as a Flash games website

00:01:19.750 --> 00:01:23.280
14 years ago and transitioned
over to mobile about four years

00:01:23.280 --> 00:01:26.740
ago, we've always been
global and bringing

00:01:26.740 --> 00:01:30.190
content to the
world the moment we

00:01:30.190 --> 00:01:32.360
deployed it, because
we started on browser.

00:01:32.360 --> 00:01:35.550
We never had any of
those issues from trying

00:01:35.550 --> 00:01:39.050
to work in the console days and
bring them to different-- NTSC

00:01:39.050 --> 00:01:41.710
to PAL, for instance.

00:01:41.710 --> 00:01:43.930
And the way we would
do that is by trying

00:01:43.930 --> 00:01:50.260
to keep the language very--
as few strings as possible

00:01:50.260 --> 00:01:51.809
and keep it very graphical.

00:01:51.809 --> 00:01:53.850
And we've continued to do
that in mobile as well.

00:01:53.850 --> 00:01:56.724
And we can discuss as we
talk how we've done that.

00:01:56.724 --> 00:01:57.390
BOB MEESE: Good.

00:01:57.390 --> 00:01:58.751
Thanks a lot.

00:01:58.751 --> 00:02:00.000
JOE RAEBURN: Hello, everybody.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:01.040
My name is Joe Raeburn.

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:03.140
I'm a producer at
Space Ape Games.

00:02:03.140 --> 00:02:05.970
We make "Samurai Siege," which
is a relatively popular combat

00:02:05.970 --> 00:02:07.120
strategy game.

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:09.470
We are live globally.

00:02:09.470 --> 00:02:11.950
We're about to go live
in Korea specifically.

00:02:11.950 --> 00:02:14.130
We had a unique
challenge in that

00:02:14.130 --> 00:02:15.519
we were a team of
just 10 people.

00:02:15.519 --> 00:02:17.060
We got together to
make a game, where

00:02:17.060 --> 00:02:19.500
we wanted to take on Supercell
and the rest of the world.

00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:22.040
And one of the things
that we had about our game

00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:24.750
is it's actually a
Japanese-themed combat strategy

00:02:24.750 --> 00:02:25.340
game.

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:26.870
We had some naysayers
saying there's

00:02:26.870 --> 00:02:28.245
no way that a
bunch of Westerners

00:02:28.245 --> 00:02:30.512
can take a Japanese-themed
combat strategy game

00:02:30.512 --> 00:02:31.470
and launch it in Japan.

00:02:31.470 --> 00:02:32.550
You must be crazy.

00:02:32.550 --> 00:02:34.930
And so for a while we let
these guys psych ourselves out.

00:02:34.930 --> 00:02:36.304
We'd done all of
the basic stuff,

00:02:36.304 --> 00:02:40.310
like in terms of basic hygiene
for localization, what Hyunse

00:02:40.310 --> 00:02:42.940
says in his presentation is
perfect-- just take that, get

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:45.460
the notes, follow it, but
don't psych yourselves out.

00:02:45.460 --> 00:02:47.720
Don't listen to people who
say your game won't work.

00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:50.745
Human beings are
fundamentally wired the same.

00:02:50.745 --> 00:02:53.480
Our brains are identical all
the way around the world.

00:02:53.480 --> 00:02:55.980
There are layers of culture
that you need to pierce through,

00:02:55.980 --> 00:02:58.040
but as long as you get through
them and you have a good game,

00:02:58.040 --> 00:02:59.290
your game will succeed.

00:02:59.290 --> 00:03:01.660
So this game that people
said, they'll never

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:05.600
like this Western Japanese game
in Japan, in fact has over 50%

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:07.240
day one retention in Japan.

00:03:07.240 --> 00:03:09.970
Monetization is twice what
it is in the United States,

00:03:09.970 --> 00:03:12.470
and the game's performing
incredibly well.

00:03:12.470 --> 00:03:15.090
So don't listen
to the naysayers.

00:03:15.090 --> 00:03:16.550
Get the basic facts right.

00:03:16.550 --> 00:03:17.310
Launch your game.

00:03:17.310 --> 00:03:17.810
Success!

00:03:20.585 --> 00:03:22.565
EYAL RABINOVICH: OK.

00:03:22.565 --> 00:03:25.040
Is it working?

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:28.010
BOB MEESE: Not yet.

00:03:28.010 --> 00:03:30.940
EYAL RABINOVICH: So my name is
Eyal, and I'm from Playscape.

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:33.232
We publish games since 2008.

00:03:33.232 --> 00:03:35.690
And I'm managing the Marketing
and the Business Development

00:03:35.690 --> 00:03:36.740
activities.

00:03:36.740 --> 00:03:38.850
We have about 50
games in the market.

00:03:38.850 --> 00:03:40.490
70 million downloads.

00:03:40.490 --> 00:03:42.930
And when it comes to
launching the games,

00:03:42.930 --> 00:03:44.300
we always do it globally.

00:03:44.300 --> 00:03:46.670
So localization is a big issue.

00:03:46.670 --> 00:03:49.440
Our approach is just
try to stay as much

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:50.600
data-driven as possible.

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:54.510
And I'm sure we can talk
about it in this panel.

00:03:54.510 --> 00:03:56.575
And that's it.

00:03:56.575 --> 00:03:57.325
BOB MEESE: Thanks.

00:03:57.325 --> 00:03:59.283
ANATOLY ROPOTOV: Let me
see if this is working.

00:03:59.283 --> 00:04:01.940
OK, my name is Anatoly, and
I'm CEO of Game Insight.

00:04:01.940 --> 00:04:04.590
Game Insight is a global game
developer, cross-platform one.

00:04:04.590 --> 00:04:07.660
We have over 30 games,
250 million players.

00:04:07.660 --> 00:04:11.140
And the biggest challenge for
us once we enter the new market

00:04:11.140 --> 00:04:13.810
is to ensure that we
could smoothly roll out

00:04:13.810 --> 00:04:17.089
at least six to seven and
even more games in operation.

00:04:17.089 --> 00:04:19.835
Our biggest genre is SIM/Tycoon
and Hidden Object, so a lot

00:04:19.835 --> 00:04:22.250
of story-driven, a
lot of localization,

00:04:22.250 --> 00:04:25.740
a lot of tailoring the
content for local markets.

00:04:25.740 --> 00:04:28.850
And our approach is typically to
tie in the launch of the games

00:04:28.850 --> 00:04:31.070
with some local
festive activity,

00:04:31.070 --> 00:04:34.630
so it'll be either holidays,
or some kind of events.

00:04:34.630 --> 00:04:36.360
Let's say, if it's
Brazil, it would

00:04:36.360 --> 00:04:38.920
be either Carnival or a
football championship,

00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:43.270
to really say that we
thinking about local players

00:04:43.270 --> 00:04:46.790
and thinking about the market
and committing ourselves

00:04:46.790 --> 00:04:50.435
to deliver the best community
management and a lot

00:04:50.435 --> 00:04:52.060
of different practices
for that market.

00:04:54.539 --> 00:04:55.580
ANTONIN LHUILLIER: Hello.

00:04:55.580 --> 00:04:56.740
I'm Antonin.

00:04:56.740 --> 00:05:01.700
I work for Gameloft
on the business side.

00:05:01.700 --> 00:05:06.320
I manage, among others,
business offices in Moscow,

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:11.150
in London, Berlin, Copenhagen,
so what we call North Europe.

00:05:11.150 --> 00:05:13.950
And I'm in charge also of
the partnership with Google

00:05:13.950 --> 00:05:16.710
at [? TMA ?] level.

00:05:16.710 --> 00:05:19.890
So we launch all
our games globally.

00:05:19.890 --> 00:05:23.420
We localize in 16 languages.

00:05:23.420 --> 00:05:26.840
We have lately started
localizing our games

00:05:26.840 --> 00:05:33.480
in Arabic language, Indonesian,
Thai, traditional Chinese.

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:36.160
So when we have a
lot of local teams,

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:40.950
we make sure that the launch
of our localized games

00:05:40.950 --> 00:05:43.170
succeed in each territory.

00:05:43.170 --> 00:05:46.960
So, in particular, we are
very-- as Anatoly said,

00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:53.030
we do a lot of in-game events
tailored to local players.

00:05:53.030 --> 00:05:56.940
We also make sure that we
address the local media.

00:05:56.940 --> 00:06:00.470
We know the local
media landscape,

00:06:00.470 --> 00:06:05.670
including in some cases the
specific social networks that

00:06:05.670 --> 00:06:08.610
are strong in a given country.

00:06:08.610 --> 00:06:10.410
Like in Korea, for
instance, you need

00:06:10.410 --> 00:06:13.520
to work with Kakao
or in some cases

00:06:13.520 --> 00:06:18.550
to integrate Kakao inside
your games to succeed.

00:06:18.550 --> 00:06:21.210
Or you need also to
address your players

00:06:21.210 --> 00:06:24.374
through VKontakte in Russia.

00:06:24.374 --> 00:06:25.040
BOB MEESE: Cool.

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:25.830
Thanks, everybody.

00:06:25.830 --> 00:06:29.910
So one of the baselines that
we've started to talk about

00:06:29.910 --> 00:06:31.394
is around localization.

00:06:31.394 --> 00:06:32.810
I've talked with
some of you guys,

00:06:32.810 --> 00:06:35.520
too, in terms of there's many
different languages that you're

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:37.166
localizing into.

00:06:37.166 --> 00:06:38.915
If you're not a native
speaker, though, it

00:06:38.915 --> 00:06:41.620
can be hard to understand
is this any good?

00:06:41.620 --> 00:06:43.520
I'm curious if you guys
have thoughts or just

00:06:43.520 --> 00:06:45.880
any suggestions
in terms of how do

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:49.070
you know when your
localization is good enough?

00:06:49.070 --> 00:06:52.150
Do you need a native speaker
for all of those languages?

00:06:52.150 --> 00:06:53.950
Or how do you guys
make that determination

00:06:53.950 --> 00:06:56.240
in terms of when your
localization for a given

00:06:56.240 --> 00:06:58.662
language is good enough
to put it out there?

00:06:58.662 --> 00:07:00.120
JOE RAEBURN: I'm
going to take that

00:07:00.120 --> 00:07:02.270
from a small studio perspective.

00:07:02.270 --> 00:07:04.860
So what we do is, we make sure
that we have excellent customer

00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:06.880
support in place when we launch.

00:07:06.880 --> 00:07:08.335
So customer support is key.

00:07:08.335 --> 00:07:10.980
It's kind of just
like Hyunse said,

00:07:10.980 --> 00:07:13.312
good App Store descriptions,
really, really good

00:07:13.312 --> 00:07:15.770
localizations, and making sure
that you have local customer

00:07:15.770 --> 00:07:17.180
support on the ground.

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:20.765
Get local customer support on
the ground relatively early so

00:07:20.765 --> 00:07:23.200
that they can start gearing
up and understanding the game.

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:25.140
And those same guys,
if they're on board

00:07:25.140 --> 00:07:26.515
and they're part
of your company,

00:07:26.515 --> 00:07:28.990
and they're playing your
game trying to understand it,

00:07:28.990 --> 00:07:32.310
what we did is we used them
as a final layer of QA.

00:07:32.310 --> 00:07:34.610
So what we're actually
doing for our new project

00:07:34.610 --> 00:07:36.580
is we're doing something
like an AB test.

00:07:36.580 --> 00:07:39.117
So we're taking one
small sliver of the game

00:07:39.117 --> 00:07:40.700
that we know and we
understand, and we

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:42.500
know that will stay the same.

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:44.708
We're putting that out to
four different localization

00:07:44.708 --> 00:07:45.430
providers.

00:07:45.430 --> 00:07:47.695
And we're assigning the
customer support agent

00:07:47.695 --> 00:07:49.570
that role of playing
through it in those four

00:07:49.570 --> 00:07:51.903
different languages or those
four different translations

00:07:51.903 --> 00:07:53.760
and saying, this
one's the best, but it

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:55.480
needs this little
bit of feedback.

00:07:55.480 --> 00:07:57.995
So because we knew that
customer support agent anyhow

00:07:57.995 --> 00:08:00.670
and because they need to
understand the game anyhow,

00:08:00.670 --> 00:08:02.950
we're essentially
getting this final level

00:08:02.950 --> 00:08:06.830
of localization choice for free.

00:08:06.830 --> 00:08:10.070
SAAD CHOUDRI: Joe, do you
guys hire people specifically

00:08:10.070 --> 00:08:11.600
in each country?

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:14.504
Or do you outsource
that customer support?

00:08:14.504 --> 00:08:15.920
JOE RAEBURN: So
we've got a system

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:18.010
where we give each
language the level of love

00:08:18.010 --> 00:08:19.009
that we want to give it.

00:08:19.009 --> 00:08:22.020
So Japanese and
Korean, for example,

00:08:22.020 --> 00:08:23.870
they are huge, huge markets.

00:08:23.870 --> 00:08:27.492
So we want to hire one person
specifically for each of those.

00:08:27.492 --> 00:08:30.520
Some of the European
languages, like, for example,

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:33.490
we are not doing
so great in Spain,

00:08:33.490 --> 00:08:35.070
and we have a few people.

00:08:35.070 --> 00:08:37.510
And Brazilian Portuguese
is quite good for us.

00:08:37.510 --> 00:08:40.000
But we might find someone in
Europe, someone from a player

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:41.594
base who really wants
to come on board that

00:08:41.594 --> 00:08:42.990
can speak two or
three languages.

00:08:42.990 --> 00:08:45.310
And we're like,
great; we'll have you.

00:08:45.310 --> 00:08:47.310
So we try to double
up on the languages

00:08:47.310 --> 00:08:50.200
where the revenue isn't so high
but have dedicated customer

00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:53.269
support for languages where
the revenue is very high.

00:08:53.269 --> 00:08:54.060
SAAD CHOUDRI: Cool.

00:08:54.060 --> 00:08:56.095
I only say that
because there's going

00:08:56.095 --> 00:08:59.740
to be studios in here who have
varying amounts of ability

00:08:59.740 --> 00:09:03.232
to actually hire people on the
ground in these territories,

00:09:03.232 --> 00:09:04.440
which are clearly high value.

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:08.000
We saw the presentation of
where revenue's coming from.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.395
But to answer the
question, it's reviews.

00:09:10.395 --> 00:09:12.030
It's user feedback.

00:09:12.030 --> 00:09:15.040
If you can start seeing your
rating go down all of a sudden

00:09:15.040 --> 00:09:17.437
once you've pushed out a
language localization build

00:09:17.437 --> 00:09:19.520
and you've not changed
anything else for the game,

00:09:19.520 --> 00:09:21.850
and it was doing well
before, you probably

00:09:21.850 --> 00:09:23.530
messed up translation somewhere.

00:09:23.530 --> 00:09:25.320
So that's probably
the best indicator.

00:09:25.320 --> 00:09:26.530
BOB MEESE: That's
the negative signal.

00:09:26.530 --> 00:09:27.830
SAAD CHOUDRI: Yeah, exactly.

00:09:27.830 --> 00:09:31.110
But if it's good, then
you get good feedback.

00:09:31.110 --> 00:09:34.346
You get your account managers
in each country saying, yeah,

00:09:34.346 --> 00:09:35.970
that's really good,
and it's well done.

00:09:35.970 --> 00:09:39.630
And to be honest, we leverage
our platform contacts, who

00:09:39.630 --> 00:09:41.440
will say, yep,
you're doing well.

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:43.080
That makes sense.

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:46.630
The example I used
in our email, Fred,

00:09:46.630 --> 00:09:51.030
was, for instance, pool
means nothing in Turkey.

00:09:51.030 --> 00:09:53.100
It just doesn't mean anything.

00:09:53.100 --> 00:09:55.130
But that's what our game
is called out there.

00:09:55.130 --> 00:09:59.670
So we were told by a fan that
no, it's American billiards.

00:09:59.670 --> 00:10:01.690
That's what you actually
need to call it.

00:10:01.690 --> 00:10:03.960
And it's still English.

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:06.360
You don't even have to change
into the Turkish language

00:10:06.360 --> 00:10:06.860
string.

00:10:06.860 --> 00:10:08.990
It's just you have
to name it what

00:10:08.990 --> 00:10:10.832
people know that game to be.

00:10:10.832 --> 00:10:12.540
And I think, Joe, you
mentioned something

00:10:12.540 --> 00:10:16.990
about the negative
connotation of samurai.

00:10:16.990 --> 00:10:19.720
JOE RAEBURN: Yeah, because
of the Sino-Japanese War,

00:10:19.720 --> 00:10:22.600
samurai isn't always perceived
with the most positive

00:10:22.600 --> 00:10:23.665
connotations.

00:10:23.665 --> 00:10:25.040
What we heard from
our research--

00:10:25.040 --> 00:10:26.320
and I'm probably going to
be corrected by someone

00:10:26.320 --> 00:10:28.740
who knows it better--
was that about one

00:10:28.740 --> 00:10:30.780
out of four people
in Korea would

00:10:30.780 --> 00:10:33.790
have a vaguely negative
reaction to the word "samurai."

00:10:33.790 --> 00:10:36.940
So what we actually
did is, in Japan

00:10:36.940 --> 00:10:39.275
it's called "Samurai Big War."

00:10:39.275 --> 00:10:41.275
We came up with a slightly
different translation

00:10:41.275 --> 00:10:43.530
in English, changed
that into Korean,

00:10:43.530 --> 00:10:45.281
bounced it off our
translation company

00:10:45.281 --> 00:10:47.530
and bounced it off our Korean
customer support people.

00:10:47.530 --> 00:10:49.030
And they said, that
name is awesome.

00:10:49.030 --> 00:10:50.020
so we went with that.

00:10:53.399 --> 00:10:55.440
EYAL RABINOVICH: So I
think the biggest operation

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:57.860
we had when it came to
translating the games

00:10:57.860 --> 00:11:00.070
and localizing them
was when we had

00:11:00.070 --> 00:11:01.900
a deal with NTT DoCoMo in Japan.

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:04.820
And they basically asked
us to take 100 games

00:11:04.820 --> 00:11:07.460
and to localize them,
which we thought,

00:11:07.460 --> 00:11:09.590
yes, OK, we can do that.

00:11:09.590 --> 00:11:10.960
But it wasn't that easy.

00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:14.330
It's so much more than
just translating the text,

00:11:14.330 --> 00:11:17.080
even if all you want to do
is just translate the text.

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:19.730
So using QA is always advisable.

00:11:19.730 --> 00:11:22.750
We had a local partner in Japan.

00:11:22.750 --> 00:11:24.899
So if you can have that,
I think that's amazing

00:11:24.899 --> 00:11:26.190
because they can play the game.

00:11:26.190 --> 00:11:27.606
They can give you
direct feedback.

00:11:27.606 --> 00:11:30.180
You have someone
to talk to, which

00:11:30.180 --> 00:11:32.920
is-- I think it might be more
advisable than just releasing

00:11:32.920 --> 00:11:34.620
the game to the
market, then starting

00:11:34.620 --> 00:11:37.330
to see your rating go down.

00:11:37.330 --> 00:11:40.440
Each point's so painful.

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:42.220
So that's what we did in Japan.

00:11:42.220 --> 00:11:45.840
And when it comes to working
with translation companies,

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:47.730
you can always ask
them to also add

00:11:47.730 --> 00:11:50.600
QA, which means
they'll play the game

00:11:50.600 --> 00:11:53.020
and see that everything
was added properly.

00:11:53.020 --> 00:11:54.260
So just do that.

00:11:54.260 --> 00:11:56.994
I think that's a
good investment.

00:11:56.994 --> 00:11:57.660
BOB MEESE: Cool.

00:12:00.075 --> 00:12:01.450
ANATOLY ROPOTOV:
At Game Insight,

00:12:01.450 --> 00:12:04.780
it's a big challenge for
us to run a lot of events

00:12:04.780 --> 00:12:07.940
and localize a lot of
content on a bi-weekly basis.

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:11.610
So we employ combined approach
of having in-house localization

00:12:11.610 --> 00:12:12.750
teams across Europe.

00:12:12.750 --> 00:12:15.080
We have some people in Germany.

00:12:15.080 --> 00:12:17.450
We have in-house French
community management.

00:12:17.450 --> 00:12:21.120
Our HQ's in Lithuania and
Riga, in Baltic states,

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:25.870
where it's easy for us to
handle operations in Russia.

00:12:25.870 --> 00:12:28.090
So we combine all that
approach out there,

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:30.040
but definitely it's a
big challenge for us

00:12:30.040 --> 00:12:32.410
with a lot of Eastern
European teams

00:12:32.410 --> 00:12:35.420
to localize that in
different languages.

00:12:35.420 --> 00:12:38.530
So first of all, those
teams would typically think,

00:12:38.530 --> 00:12:39.660
let's say, in Russian.

00:12:39.660 --> 00:12:45.310
So we have a lot of US people
in house who take that content

00:12:45.310 --> 00:12:47.940
and make it appropriate
for global markets.

00:12:47.940 --> 00:12:51.190
And then this content would
be delivered to other markets.

00:12:51.190 --> 00:12:55.620
So for us, it's a challenge
to let those teams know

00:12:55.620 --> 00:12:57.410
how they should
perceive the world.

00:12:57.410 --> 00:13:00.430
Train them in global
events across the world.

00:13:02.950 --> 00:13:04.920
Explain to them
socially acceptable

00:13:04.920 --> 00:13:07.440
practices across the world,
anything from perception

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:09.820
of vulgarity to
things like that.

00:13:09.820 --> 00:13:12.920
And surprisingly, it's sometimes
a challenge to explain that.

00:13:12.920 --> 00:13:14.795
But yeah, that's our approach.

00:13:14.795 --> 00:13:16.670
BOB MEESE: Could you
speak a little bit, too,

00:13:16.670 --> 00:13:18.045
for some of the
