00:14:03.817 --> 00:14:05.150
We're working in that direction.

00:14:05.150 --> 00:14:05.900
BOB MEESE: Thanks.

00:14:07.794 --> 00:14:09.460
ANTONIN LHUILLIER:
Yeah, so at Gameloft,

00:14:09.460 --> 00:14:14.420
we have resources
in-house for localization.

00:14:14.420 --> 00:14:20.160
And we also have localization
QA teams, especially

00:14:20.160 --> 00:14:22.730
for, let's say, more
difficult languages,

00:14:22.730 --> 00:14:26.420
like Japanese, Korean,
and also Russian.

00:14:26.420 --> 00:14:29.700
Russian is quite
demanding, because you

00:14:29.700 --> 00:14:34.420
need as much text as
English, if not more.

00:14:34.420 --> 00:14:39.050
And the characters weigh a
bit more in terms of bytes.

00:14:39.050 --> 00:14:43.970
So in some cases, we need
to stretch the translation

00:14:43.970 --> 00:14:47.630
very much, because our games
are initially made English.

00:14:47.630 --> 00:14:53.230
So we need to add
Russian text to stick

00:14:53.230 --> 00:14:57.390
to the limits which
are I'm in the games.

00:14:57.390 --> 00:15:00.670
There are specific parts of the
games, like buttons and so on,

00:15:00.670 --> 00:15:05.210
where you need sometimes to
go for a translation which

00:15:05.210 --> 00:15:07.840
is not as good as another one.

00:15:07.840 --> 00:15:11.974
But it fits the limits.

00:15:11.974 --> 00:15:12.640
BOB MEESE: Cool.

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:13.515
One other thing, too.

00:15:13.515 --> 00:15:17.850
We talked about localization
versus culturalization, right?

00:15:17.850 --> 00:15:20.400
So making more significant
changes to the game

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:22.560
beyond just translating.

00:15:22.560 --> 00:15:25.210
And so it seems like there's
a couple different opinions

00:15:25.210 --> 00:15:26.540
across this group, too.

00:15:26.540 --> 00:15:28.910
So anybody with a
particularly strong opinion

00:15:28.910 --> 00:15:33.669
in terms of either
culturalization is appropriate,

00:15:33.669 --> 00:15:34.460
or it doesn't work?

00:15:34.460 --> 00:15:38.410
And it can certainly differ
by type of game, as well, too.

00:15:38.410 --> 00:15:41.750
But just on this topic
of culturalization,

00:15:41.750 --> 00:15:44.250
anybody who wants to
talk about whether you're

00:15:44.250 --> 00:15:46.990
for it or against it for
your particular games.

00:15:49.179 --> 00:15:50.720
SAAD CHOUDRI: I
don't want it to seem

00:15:50.720 --> 00:15:52.750
like it's just binary
going down the thing.

00:15:52.750 --> 00:15:52.880
BOB MEESE: Yep.

00:15:52.880 --> 00:15:53.940
SAAD CHOUDRI: Then
also, if people--

00:15:53.940 --> 00:15:55.950
it's the last session of the
day, when most of us know--

00:15:55.950 --> 00:15:56.460
BOB MEESE: Grab a drink, yeah.

00:15:56.460 --> 00:15:57.585
SAAD CHOUDRI: Just jump in.

00:15:57.585 --> 00:15:59.420
BOB MEESE: Yeah.

00:15:59.420 --> 00:16:03.185
SAAD CHOUDRI: For us,
culturalization isn't just

00:16:03.185 --> 00:16:06.160
the art style, isn't
just the pricing.

00:16:06.160 --> 00:16:08.000
It's actually the
live operations.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:09.110
It's the events.

00:16:09.110 --> 00:16:11.510
It's when you do the
push notifications.

00:16:11.510 --> 00:16:16.140
It's like people were saying,
in Korea, it's after meal times,

00:16:16.140 --> 00:16:18.400
or it's when
they're on the Tube.

00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:22.140
I've often said that actually,
the best time for gaming

00:16:22.140 --> 00:16:26.040
in the UK would be during
the commuting hours as well,

00:16:26.040 --> 00:16:27.830
but we don't have good
Wi-Fi in the Tube.

00:16:27.830 --> 00:16:29.060
So that could all change.

00:16:29.060 --> 00:16:31.775
So for us, culturalization
is crucial.

00:16:31.775 --> 00:16:34.630
But as a company that needs
to, obviously, make profit,

00:16:34.630 --> 00:16:37.130
it's very difficult for us
to invest in these countries,

00:16:37.130 --> 00:16:39.880
because you have to
ramp up new offices.

00:16:39.880 --> 00:16:41.650
You have to find
trustworthy partners.

00:16:41.650 --> 00:16:44.500
So we do go and look
for the best people

00:16:44.500 --> 00:16:47.810
to work with in each territory.

00:16:47.810 --> 00:16:51.949
And then it's still a lot of
resources on your company.

00:16:51.949 --> 00:16:53.240
You still have to support that.

00:16:53.240 --> 00:16:55.392
You still have a
producer looking at that.

00:16:55.392 --> 00:16:57.350
And it's quite difficult,
because that producer

00:16:57.350 --> 00:16:59.690
isn't the expert in
that market, which

00:16:59.690 --> 00:17:01.240
is why you're using those guys.

00:17:01.240 --> 00:17:04.030
It's just a lot of trust.

00:17:04.030 --> 00:17:07.163
And you then don't know
if it's going to do well.

00:17:07.163 --> 00:17:08.079
There's track records.

00:17:08.079 --> 00:17:10.800
And most of us will be trying
to look at the APAC region,

00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:12.540
because it's probably the
most difficult for us all

00:17:12.540 --> 00:17:14.998
to penetrate-- apart from Joe,
who seems to have smashed it

00:17:14.998 --> 00:17:17.390
out of the park with
his "Samurai Siege."

00:17:17.390 --> 00:17:23.099
But we have to
culturalize it and not

00:17:23.099 --> 00:17:24.670
look like just localization.

00:17:24.670 --> 00:17:27.160
Because if you want to
really extract value

00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:30.260
from these regions,
players demand it,

00:17:30.260 --> 00:17:32.080
because there's so
much content out there.

00:17:32.080 --> 00:17:35.510
And if you won't do it, then
a domestic player will do it.

00:17:35.510 --> 00:17:37.270
So, yeah I think
you have to look

00:17:37.270 --> 00:17:38.870
at what works best for you.

00:17:38.870 --> 00:17:40.710
If you can do it
in-house, great.

00:17:40.710 --> 00:17:43.060
But the easiest method
is a local partner.

00:17:43.060 --> 00:17:46.402
And there's different ways
to cut that up and figure out

00:17:46.402 --> 00:17:47.860
a deal that works
for your company.

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:51.970
JOE RAEBURN: So I'm going
to talk about a funny story,

00:17:51.970 --> 00:17:52.610
not from us.

00:17:52.610 --> 00:17:55.310
But it's from when we
tried to get a better

00:17:55.310 --> 00:17:58.289
Japanese localization,
because our first one, someone

00:17:58.289 --> 00:18:00.080
looked at it and said,
that's just rubbish.

00:18:00.080 --> 00:18:01.450
That will never fly.

00:18:01.450 --> 00:18:03.640
They then told us a
story about this game.

00:18:03.640 --> 00:18:07.720
It was to do with, I
think, some farm animals.

00:18:07.720 --> 00:18:10.916
They'd got a really, really
bad localization partner.

00:18:10.916 --> 00:18:12.540
It was translated
into Japanese, but it

00:18:12.540 --> 00:18:13.820
was like broken Japanese.

00:18:16.390 --> 00:18:17.700
It made absolutely no sense.

00:18:17.700 --> 00:18:19.340
But then they just
shipped it anyway.

00:18:19.340 --> 00:18:22.420
And they shipped it, and it
was all about these little farm

00:18:22.420 --> 00:18:23.260
animals.

00:18:23.260 --> 00:18:24.802
And the game did
really, really well,

00:18:24.802 --> 00:18:26.426
because players
laughed at it and said,

00:18:26.426 --> 00:18:28.060
this Western art
style is so funny.

00:18:28.060 --> 00:18:30.060
They all talk in
such a funny way.

00:18:30.060 --> 00:18:31.620
They're such funny,
funny characters.

00:18:31.620 --> 00:18:32.880
And they're so cute.

00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:35.300
So I guess the moral of
that that you can take away

00:18:35.300 --> 00:18:39.530
is ultimately what really
matters are your stats.

00:18:39.530 --> 00:18:42.230
If you're not looking at your
day one retention, if you're

00:18:42.230 --> 00:18:43.210
not looking at your
day seven retention,

00:18:43.210 --> 00:18:44.660
if you're not looking
at your monetization,

00:18:44.660 --> 00:18:46.489
if you're not looking
at your reviews,

00:18:46.489 --> 00:18:48.280
then you're not looking
at the right stuff.

00:18:48.280 --> 00:18:50.150
And there might
be one, like, I'd

00:18:50.150 --> 00:18:51.690
love to say, yes,
fully culturalize

00:18:51.690 --> 00:18:54.180
your game for every single
territory out there.

00:18:54.180 --> 00:18:57.000
With unlimited manpower,
with a 6,000-person company,

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.250
I highly recommend
that's what you do.

00:18:59.250 --> 00:19:01.360
If you've got a team
of 15 people trying

00:19:01.360 --> 00:19:03.930
to make a difference,
then you really

00:19:03.930 --> 00:19:05.210
have to pick your battles.

00:19:05.210 --> 00:19:07.210
And what we saw when we
translated into Japanese

00:19:07.210 --> 00:19:08.890
is it was just one
thing that really

00:19:08.890 --> 00:19:10.300
wasn't cutting the mustard.

00:19:10.300 --> 00:19:12.634
If you've ever logged into a
game like "Rage of Bahamut"

00:19:12.634 --> 00:19:14.341
or any similar games,
you know that there

00:19:14.341 --> 00:19:15.850
are lots and lots
of live events.

00:19:15.850 --> 00:19:16.840
When you log in,
you see something

00:19:16.840 --> 00:19:18.965
that looks like a web page--
because effectively it

00:19:18.965 --> 00:19:21.860
is a web page-- and it will say
something like, 17th of August!

00:19:21.860 --> 00:19:22.837
19th of August!

00:19:22.837 --> 00:19:23.420
Special event!

00:19:23.420 --> 00:19:26.240
Exclamation point,
exclamation point.

00:19:26.240 --> 00:19:30.860
That's actually a very,
very distinct coded language

00:19:30.860 --> 00:19:32.931
in the way that they talk
about events in Japan.

00:19:32.931 --> 00:19:35.430
And we run a lot of live events
in our game "Samurai Siege."

00:19:35.430 --> 00:19:37.080
We looked at Asian
games for inspiration.

00:19:37.080 --> 00:19:39.100
And we wanted to be able
to do that in the West,

00:19:39.100 --> 00:19:42.420
and they just weren't getting
communicated correctly.

00:19:42.420 --> 00:19:44.580
And again, our Japanese
customer support

00:19:44.580 --> 00:19:47.280
person said, let me just
take what you've got

00:19:47.280 --> 00:19:49.110
and mock it up in Photoshop.

00:19:49.110 --> 00:19:51.510
And although event
screens are normally

00:19:51.510 --> 00:19:54.690
kind of like-- not HTML, but
a template-driven environment

00:19:54.690 --> 00:19:57.050
where you put translated
text over the top,

00:19:57.050 --> 00:19:58.640
and it renders it
in-game in Arial

00:19:58.640 --> 00:20:00.750
or whatever font
we're using, we just

00:20:00.750 --> 00:20:02.850
decided to do single
images for Japan

00:20:02.850 --> 00:20:05.740
that she made in Photoshop, and
she copy-pasted it in there.

00:20:05.740 --> 00:20:08.482
And then the response to
those event pages went way up.

00:20:08.482 --> 00:20:10.940
And then we tried it on Japanese
players, and they're like,

00:20:10.940 --> 00:20:11.523
you know what?

00:20:11.523 --> 00:20:13.739
There's not really anything
that's wrong with what

00:20:13.739 --> 00:20:14.280
you're doing.

00:20:14.280 --> 00:20:17.130
And so we went, OK,
let's launch it.

00:20:17.130 --> 00:20:18.890
On the thing around
notifications,

00:20:18.890 --> 00:20:23.160
I think there's been a lot of
underlying theme of designing

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:24.260
for people's lives.

00:20:24.260 --> 00:20:26.782
And essentially, that's
designing for humans.

00:20:26.782 --> 00:20:28.490
If you think about
when is the right time

00:20:28.490 --> 00:20:30.570
to push someone, yes, if
you're going to send out

00:20:30.570 --> 00:20:32.880
a bulk push to your
entire customer base,

00:20:32.880 --> 00:20:36.220
then doing it at 2:00 AM is
a really, really bad move.

00:20:36.220 --> 00:20:38.980
You're not going to
get too many responses.

00:20:38.980 --> 00:20:41.770
But if you start thinking about,
how does my notification system

00:20:41.770 --> 00:20:42.090
work?

00:20:42.090 --> 00:20:43.465
And how does it
take into account

00:20:43.465 --> 00:20:45.630
what time-- the players
playing patterns?

00:20:45.630 --> 00:20:47.940
Like if they always
log in at 7:00 AM,

00:20:47.940 --> 00:20:52.294
then maybe the notification
should come at 6:59 AM

00:20:52.294 --> 00:20:53.960
to match up with what
their schedule is.

00:20:53.960 --> 00:20:59.040
You don't need to have 200
producers, or 20 producers,

00:20:59.040 --> 00:21:01.580
or 10 producers looking at
what the right times are

00:21:01.580 --> 00:21:02.580
in each country.

00:21:02.580 --> 00:21:05.120
You have analytics and
data and player patterns.

00:21:05.120 --> 00:21:09.070
And you can just create nice
human-centric scheduling

00:21:09.070 --> 00:21:11.262
things that work for humans.

00:21:11.262 --> 00:21:12.720
And you'll find
that generally they

00:21:12.720 --> 00:21:14.730
will work for humans
all the world around.

00:21:14.730 --> 00:21:17.757
And find what the exceptions
are and fix the exceptions,

00:21:17.757 --> 00:21:19.590
and you'll end up
culturalizing a few things

00:21:19.590 --> 00:21:22.870
rather than
culturalizing everything.

00:21:22.870 --> 00:21:24.740
EYAL RABINOVICH:
So I think there

00:21:24.740 --> 00:21:27.640
are two main approaches when
it comes to localization.

00:21:27.640 --> 00:21:29.745
You can, first of all,
decide which countries

00:21:29.745 --> 00:21:32.730
you want to localize your
game to, select the top 10,

00:21:32.730 --> 00:21:35.380
and localize before
you launch the game.

00:21:35.380 --> 00:21:38.950
And you can also start launching
the game in one language,

00:21:38.950 --> 00:21:42.775
and see which one catches up,
and just translate and localize

00:21:42.775 --> 00:21:44.230
as you go.

00:21:44.230 --> 00:21:46.810
This is the way even GooglePlay
recommends you to do that.

00:21:46.810 --> 00:21:48.795
They give you
suggestions whenever

00:21:48.795 --> 00:21:50.420
they see that you
have a user base that

00:21:50.420 --> 00:21:52.310
grows in a specific country.

00:21:52.310 --> 00:21:55.462
And the second approach is a
little bit more data-driven.

00:21:55.462 --> 00:21:56.920
But it also means
that you're going

00:21:56.920 --> 00:21:58.930
to launch a game
that is not fully

00:21:58.930 --> 00:22:00.510
baked for a specific language.

00:22:00.510 --> 00:22:03.530
So there are pros and cons
for each one of those.

00:22:03.530 --> 00:22:06.610
The second thing I would
like you to think about

00:22:06.610 --> 00:22:10.360
is the fact that you're going
to localize the game for top 10

00:22:10.360 --> 00:22:13.500
languages, but you're not
going to be able to localize it

00:22:13.500 --> 00:22:15.970
to all the languages
you have in your game.

00:22:15.970 --> 00:22:18.420
Just too costly, and
the operational costs

00:22:18.420 --> 00:22:20.330
are also something
to be considered.

00:22:20.330 --> 00:22:25.050
So you're going to have
a big category of players

00:22:25.050 --> 00:22:28.519
that are considered to be in the
"other" category that are going

00:22:28.519 --> 00:22:29.810
to play a version of your game.

00:22:29.810 --> 00:22:32.670
And you have to think
about how that version is

00:22:32.670 --> 00:22:35.250
going to look like.

00:22:35.250 --> 00:22:39.560
I don't think that necessarily
going for an English version

00:22:39.560 --> 00:22:41.300
would be the right choice.

00:22:41.300 --> 00:22:43.680
So what we have been
doing is we started

00:22:43.680 --> 00:22:45.520
to think about how
we can globalize

00:22:45.520 --> 00:22:46.747
a version of the game.

00:22:46.747 --> 00:22:48.830
It will be played by people
that don't necessarily

00:22:48.830 --> 00:22:54.150
speak English, but we are
not likely to localize

00:22:54.150 --> 00:22:55.440
the game for.

00:22:55.440 --> 00:22:58.350
And actually, it shows
us really good results,

00:22:58.350 --> 00:23:02.330
both in retention
and in monetization.

00:23:02.330 --> 00:23:06.030
And so I think you have
to be kind of flexible

00:23:06.030 --> 00:23:07.490
and mix different
approaches if you

00:23:07.490 --> 00:23:08.730
want to be able to scale up.

00:23:08.730 --> 00:23:10.860
It's not something that--
there's no paradigm.

00:23:10.860 --> 00:23:12.810
And sometimes you
localize the game,

00:23:12.810 --> 00:23:14.497
and it doesn't show any results.

00:23:14.497 --> 00:23:16.080
BOB MEESE: Could you
repeat that, too?

00:23:16.080 --> 00:23:19.020
Because you shared a really
good visual earlier, too,

00:23:19.020 --> 00:23:22.524
in terms of what that solution
was for the other group.

00:23:22.524 --> 00:23:24.190
Could you talk about
that a little more?

00:23:24.190 --> 00:23:26.481
EYAL RABINOVICH: Yeah, so
basically it's really simple.

00:23:26.481 --> 00:23:28.630
And what's nice about
it is that globalization

00:23:28.630 --> 00:23:30.577
doesn't take a lot of
resources because you

00:23:30.577 --> 00:23:31.910
don't have to have translations.

00:23:31.910 --> 00:23:35.100
What you have to do
is to think about what

00:23:35.100 --> 00:23:37.480
are the strings in
your game that you

00:23:37.480 --> 00:23:39.830
can replace with
intuitive icons.

00:23:39.830 --> 00:23:43.300
And by the way, even if the
icons are not very intuitive,

00:23:43.300 --> 00:23:45.620
it's sometimes just good
to put them out there.

00:23:45.620 --> 00:23:48.050
If they're not taking a
prominent part of the game,

00:23:48.050 --> 00:23:50.957
people will just click on it
later on and see what it does.

00:23:50.957 --> 00:23:53.040
So we took the main menu
of "Ninja Chicken," which

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:56.240
is one of our more
successful franchises,

00:23:56.240 --> 00:23:58.110
and we just replaced
a few of the buttons

00:23:58.110 --> 00:24:00.770
with icons that we
thought that made sense.

00:24:00.770 --> 00:24:02.735
And after doing
so, we actually saw

00:24:02.735 --> 00:24:05.490
that some of the
English-speaking segments,

00:24:05.490 --> 00:24:08.734
actually, even react better
to these modifications.

00:24:08.734 --> 00:24:10.150
So it's kind of
interesting to see

00:24:10.150 --> 00:24:11.525
how people react
to casual games.

00:24:11.525 --> 00:24:14.077
I think it's
specifically-- I mean,

00:24:14.077 --> 00:24:15.410
you can do it with casual games.

00:24:15.410 --> 00:24:17.850
I don't think that mid-core
games and hard-core games

00:24:17.850 --> 00:24:19.670
would be suitable
for this approach.

00:24:19.670 --> 00:24:22.510
But if you have a game that
is not very text-intensive,

00:24:22.510 --> 00:24:24.260
I think you should
be able to think

00:24:24.260 --> 00:24:25.593
about how you do it that way.

00:24:29.242 --> 00:24:31.450
ANATOLY ROPOTOV: We employ
some data-driven practices

00:24:31.450 --> 00:24:37.195
to figure out if certain
countries performing less,

00:24:37.195 --> 00:24:38.810
is performing worse than others.

00:24:38.810 --> 00:24:42.800
So just looking at things
like the total completion

00:24:42.800 --> 00:24:45.150
rates, retention rates
for that country,

00:24:45.150 --> 00:24:46.610
is kind of a signal
to figure out

00:24:46.610 --> 00:24:49.620
if something is wrong with
localization or content

00:24:49.620 --> 00:24:51.470
approach, and things like that.

00:24:51.470 --> 00:24:53.960
And then I would
definitely benchmark

00:24:53.960 --> 00:24:56.650
against English
and Russian, which

00:24:56.650 --> 00:24:59.280
would be always perfect for
us, and we would figure out

00:24:59.280 --> 00:25:01.070
if something is
wrong here and there.

00:25:01.070 --> 00:25:03.650
And the coolest thing in the
Google Developer Console,

00:25:03.650 --> 00:25:06.840
that a lot of times it
gives signals, and talks

00:25:06.840 --> 00:25:10.260
about this region
is starting to grow,

00:25:10.260 --> 00:25:12.682
but you actually don't
have localization for that.

00:25:12.682 --> 00:25:14.530
For some of the
games, we would launch

00:25:14.530 --> 00:25:16.560
with few languages in beta.

00:25:16.560 --> 00:25:19.070
For some others, we would
definitely go all in

00:25:19.070 --> 00:25:22.720
and say seven, eight, at least,
languages, up to even 10.

00:25:22.720 --> 00:25:25.260
But then it all
really comes down

00:25:25.260 --> 00:25:27.210
to whether these
countries could monetize

00:25:27.210 --> 00:25:28.840
with this type of games.

00:25:28.840 --> 00:25:32.730
If, let's say, female
players in a certain country

00:25:32.730 --> 00:25:34.459
have those payment methods.

00:25:34.459 --> 00:25:36.500
They have debit cards,
and the couldn't use them.

00:25:36.500 --> 00:25:39.320
So you have to be really
careful about that.

00:25:39.320 --> 00:25:41.420
You have to go region
by region and figure out

00:25:41.420 --> 00:25:45.230
if certain localization is
appropriate for that region.

00:25:45.230 --> 00:25:50.180
But it's sometimes a challenging
to localize some of our games,

00:25:50.180 --> 00:25:52.460
like hidden-object
games, because

00:25:52.460 --> 00:25:54.710
for hidden-object games,
it's a huge challenge

00:25:54.710 --> 00:25:57.840
to create the glossary with
visual things out there.

00:25:57.840 --> 00:26:01.040
So people would definitely
identify a single word

00:26:01.040 --> 00:26:03.820
with a shape, with
an image out there.

00:26:03.820 --> 00:26:06.730
And if a localization
team doesn't

00:26:06.730 --> 00:26:09.754
have a great visual glossary,
let's say, this is a glass,

00:26:09.754 --> 00:26:11.420
or this is a mirror,
and they would just

00:26:11.420 --> 00:26:14.360
localize a word without
actually looking at the object

00:26:14.360 --> 00:26:17.450
and perceiving the context
of the subject in the game,

00:26:17.450 --> 00:26:19.997
we would definitely see a
game performing really bad.

00:26:19.997 --> 00:26:22.163
And we would have to throw
out the full localization

00:26:22.163 --> 00:26:26.400
and go from scratch and explain
to the localization team

00:26:26.400 --> 00:26:27.560
how to approach that.

00:26:27.560 --> 00:26:29.910
So definitely, different
games and genres

00:26:29.910 --> 00:26:31.540
have different approach for us.

00:26:31.540 --> 00:26:35.260
And in a lot of countries,
it's a challenge

00:26:35.260 --> 00:26:42.840
to have social context and
to achieve as good results

00:26:42.840 --> 00:26:45.620
as in other countries.

00:26:45.620 --> 00:26:47.860
ANTONIN LHUILLIER: So I
said that the first step

00:26:47.860 --> 00:26:53.490
for culturalization is
also your portfolio,

00:26:53.490 --> 00:26:55.350
because you need some games.

00:26:55.350 --> 00:26:59.300
I mean, they won't
work in some places.

00:26:59.300 --> 00:27:03.800
So we see that when we launched,
for instance, "Spiderman

00:27:03.800 --> 00:27:08.820
Unlimited," it works greatly
in the UK and the US.

00:27:08.820 --> 00:27:14.540
And players from
other territories

00:27:14.540 --> 00:27:17.600
won't necessarily maybe
not even know Spiderman.

00:27:17.600 --> 00:27:21.082
I don't know, but
it's an IP which--

00:27:21.082 --> 00:27:22.540
SAAD CHOUDRI: How
is that possible?

00:27:22.540 --> 00:27:24.830
Everybody knows Spiderman.

00:27:24.830 --> 00:27:27.820
ANTONIN LHUILLIER:
So far, and in some

00:27:27.820 --> 00:27:31.580
territories, we
basically feel that you

00:27:31.580 --> 00:27:36.220
need to go really to localize
the business model also,

00:27:36.220 --> 00:27:40.250
as Rahim said before.

00:27:40.250 --> 00:27:45.230
So, for instance, in Japan--
and also the session on Korea

00:27:45.230 --> 00:27:47.020
was interesting from
this point of view--

00:27:47.020 --> 00:27:53.730
is there is [INAUDIBLE], so we
have tweaked some of our games

00:27:53.730 --> 00:27:57.190
to make them fit
the monetization

00:27:57.190 --> 00:27:59.520
habits of some customers.

00:27:59.520 --> 00:28:02.920
So let's say that's the
very first step that we take

00:28:02.920 --> 00:28:06.600
at Gameloft to be
a global player is

00:28:06.600 --> 00:28:08.890
to have a very wide
portfolio of titles

00:28:08.890 --> 00:28:17.080
and to try to please
to any customer,

00:28:17.080 --> 00:28:19.774
to have something for everyone.

00:28:19.774 --> 00:28:20.440
BOB MEESE: Cool.

00:28:20.440 --> 00:28:22.090
Any other questions
from the audience?

00:28:22.090 --> 00:28:24.369
