00:28:24.369 --> 00:28:26.744
AUDIENCE: What do you think
about community translations?

00:28:26.744 --> 00:28:29.882
Is it too risky, or it's a good
way to engage with the users?

00:28:29.882 --> 00:28:31.840
BOB MEESE: So the question
is just what do they

00:28:31.840 --> 00:28:34.020
think about community
translations?

00:28:34.020 --> 00:28:38.420
Is it a good way to engage
with users or too risky?

00:28:38.420 --> 00:28:42.670
SAAD CHOUDRI: We get probably
in the general emails

00:28:42.670 --> 00:28:49.010
where people say, hey,
I'm from random country

00:28:49.010 --> 00:28:52.410
X. I love your game.

00:28:52.410 --> 00:28:53.410
I want to translate it.

00:28:53.410 --> 00:28:56.110
I think there will be a
really big market for it.

00:28:56.110 --> 00:28:58.340
It's one of those things
that comes down to trust.

00:28:58.340 --> 00:29:02.430
He could be a language
professor at a university.

00:29:02.430 --> 00:29:03.920
We have had that.

00:29:03.920 --> 00:29:07.660
But we've still not gone through
the process, because sometimes,

00:29:07.660 --> 00:29:10.930
the truth is, it's
just that market for us

00:29:10.930 --> 00:29:13.750
hasn't really got
the traction that we

00:29:13.750 --> 00:29:15.254
need to justify doing it.

00:29:15.254 --> 00:29:16.670
So somebody in the
community could

00:29:16.670 --> 00:29:20.330
do the language localization
and get it out there,

00:29:20.330 --> 00:29:24.110
but again, it's time, effort,
and resources, really,

00:29:24.110 --> 00:29:25.300
that comes down to it.

00:29:25.300 --> 00:29:26.760
But why not?

00:29:26.760 --> 00:29:27.750
It could be good.

00:29:27.750 --> 00:29:28.590
Try it.

00:29:28.590 --> 00:29:29.329
Check it out.

00:29:29.329 --> 00:29:31.120
BOB MEESE: We don't
need to test everybody.

00:29:31.120 --> 00:29:32.290
Anybody have a
different point of view?

00:29:32.290 --> 00:29:34.115
Anybody in favor of
community translation?

00:29:37.020 --> 00:29:38.660
ANATOLY ROPOTOV:
Well, as our games

00:29:38.660 --> 00:29:41.710
are being updated
every few weeks here

00:29:41.710 --> 00:29:44.810
and there, it's kind
of hard to stick

00:29:44.810 --> 00:29:48.440
to a single
outsourced person who

00:29:48.440 --> 00:29:50.760
likes the game enough
to localize it,

00:29:50.760 --> 00:29:53.170
perhaps for a month or two.

00:29:53.170 --> 00:29:57.750
But I think this applies more
to in the casual single-player

00:29:57.750 --> 00:30:00.030
games, it could
be localized once,

00:30:00.030 --> 00:30:03.430
and then the developer
would definitely see benefit

00:30:03.430 --> 00:30:05.060
from sales from this region.

00:30:05.060 --> 00:30:07.910
He could approach blogs in that
region, and things like that.

00:30:07.910 --> 00:30:11.876
But so far, we
haven't done that.

00:30:11.876 --> 00:30:12.832
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:18.390 --> 00:30:19.970
BOB MEESE: Could you get a mic?

00:30:19.970 --> 00:30:20.856
Can you pass a mic?

00:30:24.620 --> 00:30:26.420
All right.

00:30:26.420 --> 00:30:29.000
AUDIENCE: So we use
Crowdin to handle

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:30.660
some crowd-sourced
localizations,

00:30:30.660 --> 00:30:33.000
and it's actually
been very helpful.

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:35.500
It's a good way to just hit the
languages which you wouldn't

00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:36.750
really bother doing otherwise.

00:30:36.750 --> 00:30:38.180
So a lot of the
Nordic countries,

00:30:38.180 --> 00:30:40.100
English works fine for us.

00:30:40.100 --> 00:30:43.070
But then we've got
about 5,000 people

00:30:43.070 --> 00:30:45.770
who have been working
on translating

00:30:45.770 --> 00:30:48.860
the game into multiple
different languages.

00:30:48.860 --> 00:30:52.150
There's no cost to it, except
for it costs $20 a month

00:30:52.150 --> 00:30:53.700
or something to
set up the system.

00:30:53.700 --> 00:30:55.550
And as long as you
have an automated way

00:30:55.550 --> 00:30:58.350
to handle the strings, you
can have as many languages

00:30:58.350 --> 00:30:59.600
as your community wants to do.

00:30:59.600 --> 00:31:01.630
And then you can see
if it's worth, then,

00:31:01.630 --> 00:31:04.730
investing in having a proper
translation done down the line.

00:31:04.730 --> 00:31:10.385
So if you've got the community,
I think it's worth doing.

00:31:10.385 --> 00:31:13.042
BOB MEESE: Any other
questions out there?

00:31:13.042 --> 00:31:16.217
AUDIENCE: We're taking about
translation and localization.

00:31:16.217 --> 00:31:17.550
BOB MEESE: Want to pass it over?

00:31:22.520 --> 00:31:25.950
AUDIENCE: We're talking about
localization and translation.

00:31:25.950 --> 00:31:29.510
And I wanted to ask if you
do just the text localization

00:31:29.510 --> 00:31:33.510
where you keep the voiceover
and the original in English,

00:31:33.510 --> 00:31:34.430
for instance?

00:31:34.430 --> 00:31:38.170
Or do you do both, or
like a complete package?

00:31:38.170 --> 00:31:41.820
And if it's actually
worth doing just the text

00:31:41.820 --> 00:31:44.170
and then having the voiceover
in English, whether it's

00:31:44.170 --> 00:31:47.130
having actually a worse
impact than just leaving it

00:31:47.130 --> 00:31:49.170
in English?

00:31:49.170 --> 00:31:50.840
ANATOLY ROPOTOV:
So at Game Insight,

00:31:50.840 --> 00:31:53.170
we have a title called
"Tank Domination," which

00:31:53.170 --> 00:31:54.830
came out earlier this year.

00:31:54.830 --> 00:31:56.700
We launched it at GDC.

00:31:56.700 --> 00:32:00.880
And it features Michael Ironside
from "Starship Troopers,"

00:32:00.880 --> 00:32:02.500
a famous US actor out there.

00:32:02.500 --> 00:32:05.135
And he voiceovered that for US.

00:32:05.135 --> 00:32:06.990
For Russia, we used
a different person

00:32:06.990 --> 00:32:11.740
who does VO for a lot of movies,
and he's kind of a famous star.

00:32:11.740 --> 00:32:13.470
And then we would have
a similar approach

00:32:13.470 --> 00:32:15.820
for a lot of our trailers
and a lot of our content.

00:32:15.820 --> 00:32:17.560
If you have that,
you definitely have

00:32:17.560 --> 00:32:19.330
to think from a
marketing perspective

00:32:19.330 --> 00:32:24.660
how you could leverage the power
of famous voices, famous actors

00:32:24.660 --> 00:32:26.700
on a region-by-region
basis, whether it

00:32:26.700 --> 00:32:29.190
could make a significant
impact and how

00:32:29.190 --> 00:32:34.690
you could make that a part
of your marketing strategy.

00:32:34.690 --> 00:32:37.760
And we found out that
it's really worth

00:32:37.760 --> 00:32:40.090
that, because endorsements
of celebrities, as you know

00:32:40.090 --> 00:32:43.045
from a lot of recent
launches by other companies,

00:32:43.045 --> 00:32:47.361
are very powerful, so you
definitely have to do that,

00:32:47.361 --> 00:32:47.861
yeah.

00:32:50.541 --> 00:32:52.540
EYAL RABINOVICH: We have
a game in the pipeline.

00:32:52.540 --> 00:32:56.330
Not out yet, but hopefully
you hear about it.

00:32:56.330 --> 00:32:58.210
And it's very voice-intensive.

00:32:58.210 --> 00:33:00.410
You have a lot of text
and a lot of voice.

00:33:00.410 --> 00:33:03.420
And it creates some kind
of a unique experience.

00:33:03.420 --> 00:33:06.160
But I think that we
are then definitely

00:33:06.160 --> 00:33:10.500
going to have to go for
the full localization.

00:33:10.500 --> 00:33:14.530
Even some modification in the
storyline might have to happen.

00:33:14.530 --> 00:33:17.380
So, like everything,
I think it kind of

00:33:17.380 --> 00:33:19.530
depends on the
content in a game.

00:33:19.530 --> 00:33:23.604
And you have to consider
everything case by case.

00:33:23.604 --> 00:33:24.145
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:33:24.145 --> 00:33:25.558
Thank you.

00:33:25.558 --> 00:33:26.204
Can I just--

00:33:26.204 --> 00:33:27.120
EYAL RABINOVICH: Jeez.

00:33:27.120 --> 00:33:28.310
OK.

00:33:28.310 --> 00:33:30.150
It would be probably
for Antonin,

00:33:30.150 --> 00:33:33.070
because we are producing
a shooter as well.

00:33:33.070 --> 00:33:34.530
And so basically,
the question, OK,

00:33:34.530 --> 00:33:37.300
is should we just translate?

00:33:37.300 --> 00:33:40.410
We're a team of 21 people.

00:33:40.410 --> 00:33:42.470
So we don't have the resources.

00:33:42.470 --> 00:33:46.430
So does it make sense to
just translate the text

00:33:46.430 --> 00:33:49.710
and leave the rest in
English, the voiceover?

00:33:49.710 --> 00:33:51.750
ANTONIN LHUILLIER: Yeah,
I think it makes sense.

00:33:51.750 --> 00:33:53.220
I think it makes sense.

00:33:53.220 --> 00:33:55.250
There are some
games from Gameloft

00:33:55.250 --> 00:33:57.490
where you have
very sophisticated

00:33:57.490 --> 00:34:01.060
English voiceovers with
the voices from the actors,

00:34:01.060 --> 00:34:05.130
of all the ponies from the
ponies in "My Little Pony,"

00:34:05.130 --> 00:34:07.860
for instance, and
we don't localize.

00:34:07.860 --> 00:34:09.780
There are subtitles.

00:34:09.780 --> 00:34:13.810
So I think for a shooter,
the main pleasure

00:34:13.810 --> 00:34:17.065
that players will take from the
shooter is to actually shoot

00:34:17.065 --> 00:34:18.770
in the action scene.

00:34:18.770 --> 00:34:23.739
So if you make some good
sound effects, it's fine.

00:34:23.739 --> 00:34:27.448
Then they don't need
to be localized.

00:34:27.448 --> 00:34:28.763
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:34:28.763 --> 00:34:30.304
BOB MEESE: Can you
pass the mic over?

